Language Model¶

Natural Language Processing (NLP) describes the field of Artificial Intelligence dealing with textual data. In this chapter we study a particular application of this field called Language Modeling (LM). LM consists in building models that have to output the next word given a context, a collection of previous words. Such model is trained to maximize the probability of the next word in a given dictionary. LM can be used for User Interfaces where the model can help the user wrtie text faster, in text generation tasks to generate new sentences in the style of a given writer and more.

Here we attempt to build a Language Model based on J. K. Rowling's Harry Potter Books.

Data¶

This section describes the data processing and the building of the dataset for training our LM.

Curation¶

The Harry Potter Books class is responsible for collecting all the Harry Potter books and assemble them into one text file to be further processed.

In [ ]:
class HarryPotterBooks:
    base = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/formcept/whiteboard/master/nbviewer/notebooks/data/harrypotter"
    urls = [
        os.path.join(base, "Book%201%20-%20The%20Philosopher's%20Stone.txt"),
        os.path.join(base, "Book%202%20-%20The%20Chamber%20of%20Secrets.txt"),
        os.path.join(base, "Book%203%20-%20The%20Prisoner%20of%20Azkaban.txt"),
        os.path.join(base, "Book%204%20-%20The%20Goblet%20of%20Fire.txt"),
        os.path.join(base, "Book%205%20-%20The%20Order%20of%20the%20Phoenix.txt"),
        os.path.join(base, "Book%206%20-%20The%20Half%20Blood%20Prince.txt"),
        os.path.join(base, "Book%207%20-%20The%20Deathly%20Hallows.txt"),
    ]

    def __init__(self, path: str, download: bool = True) -> None:
        self.path = path
        if download: self._download()

    def _download(self) -> None:
        if not os.path.isfile(self.path):
            with open(self.path, "a") as fp:
                for hp_book_url in self.urls:
                    request = requests.get(hp_book_url, allow_redirects=True)
                    fp.write(request.content.decode("utf-8"))

    def read_lines(self) -> list[str]:
        with open(self.path, "r") as fp:
            return fp.readlines()

Preprocessing¶

The Preprocessor class provides methods to help in the preprocessing of the books. It is reponsible for removing the empty lines, removing unnecessary informations such as the chapter number, replacing abbreviations by their full versions, and removing the end of line symbols.

In [ ]:
class HarryPotterLinePreprocessor:
    @staticmethod
    def remove_empty_lines(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        return [l for l in lines if l not in ["/ \n", "\n"]]

    @staticmethod
    def remove_chapter_names(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        return [l for l in lines if sum((c.isupper() or c in [" ", "\n"] for c in l)) != len(l)]

    @staticmethod
    def remove_page_declaration(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        return [l for l in lines if not (l.startswith("Page | ") or l.endswith("J.K. Rowling "))]

    @staticmethod
    def to_lowercase(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        return [l.lower() for l in lines]

    @staticmethod
    def replace_symbols(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        lines = list(lines)
        for abbr, full in {
            "“"          : "\"",
            "”"          : "\"",
            "''"         : "\"",
            "``"         : "\"",
            "’’"         : "\"",
            "'"          : "'",
            "`"          : "'",
            "’"          : "'",
            "jr."        : "junior",
            "sr."        : "senior",
            "mr."        : "mister",
            "mrs."       : "miss",
            "dr."        : "doctor",
            "don't"      : "do not",
            "won't"      : "will not",
            "wouldn't"   : "would not",
            "shouldn't"  : "should not",
            "isn't"      : "is not",
            "wasn't"     : "was not",
            "can't"      : "cannot",
            "i'm"        : "i am",
            "you're"     : "you are",
            "you'd"      : "you would",
            "we're"      : "we are",
            "they're"    : "they are",
            "that's"     : "that is",
            "there's"    : "there is",
            "who's"      : "who is",
            "what's"     : "what is",
            "where's"    : "where is",
            "how's"      : "how is",
            "let's"      : "let us",
            "i've"       : "i have",
            "i'd"        : "i had",
            "haven't"    : "have not",
            "hadn't"     : "had not",
            "hasn't"     : "has not",
            "aint't"     : "am not",
            "shouldn’ta" :"should not you",
        }.items(): lines = [l.replace(abbr, full) for l in lines]
        return lines

    @staticmethod
    def replace_numbers(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        replace = lambda x: num2words.num2words(int(x.group(0)))
        return [re.sub(r"\d+", replace, l) for l in lines]

    @staticmethod
    def remove_end_of_line(lines: list[str]) -> list[str]:
        return [l.replace("\n", "").strip() for l in lines]

    @staticmethod
    def preprocess(lines: list[str], join: bool = True) -> list[str] | str:
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.remove_empty_lines(lines)
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.remove_end_of_line(lines)
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.remove_chapter_names(lines)
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.remove_page_declaration(lines)
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.to_lowercase(lines)
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.replace_numbers(lines)
        lines = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.replace_symbols(lines)
        return " ".join(lines) if join else lines

Processor¶

The Processor class provides methods for splitting the raw text into word tokens and further process them.

In [ ]:
class HarryPotterProcessor:
    @staticmethod
    def extract_tokens(raw: str) -> list[str]:
        return word_tokenize(raw, language="english")

    @staticmethod
    def extract(raw: str) -> list[str]:
        return HarryPotterProcessor.extract_tokens(raw)

Vocabulary¶

The Vocab class represents the dictionary of token, the vocabulary available for the model. It automatically builds itself from the collection of tokens provided and generates two useful mappings, from token string to index, and from token index to string.

In [ ]:
class Vocab:
    def __init__(self, tokens: list[str], min_freq: int) -> None:
        self.tokens, self.min_freq = tokens, min_freq
        self._stoi = {s: i for i, (s, count) in enumerate(self._token_freq_pairs()) if count >= min_freq}
        self._itos = {i: s for s, i in self._stoi.items()}

    def _token_freq_pairs(self) -> list[tuple[str, int]]:
        return list(OrderedDict(Counter(self.tokens).most_common()).items())

    def __len__(self) -> int: return len(self._stoi)
    def stoi(self, s: str) -> int: return self._stoi[s]
    def itos(self, i: int) -> str: return self._itos[i]

Dataset¶

The Dataset class acts as a data iterator for the LM building task. It generates pairs of context tokens and a corresponding next word token for every possible fitting window in the provided token collection. It makes use of the preprocessorn and the processor to build a vocabulary as well as the training pairs.

An optional prop (proportion) argument can be passed to the constructor to limit the dataset to a certain proportion of its full length. This property can be helpful for training LM models on a smaller set, and iterate faster by limitting the amount of data.

In [ ]:
class HarryPotterNextTokenDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, path: str, context_size: int, prop: float = 1.0) -> None:
        super().__init__()
        self.path = path
        self.context_size = context_size
        self.window_size = context_size + 1
        self.prop = prop
        
        self.lines  = HarryPotterBooks(path, download=True).read_lines()
        self.raw = HarryPotterLinePreprocessor.preprocess(self.lines, join=True)
        self.tokens = HarryPotterProcessor.extract(self.raw)
        self.tokens = self.tokens[:int(self.prop * len(self.tokens))]
        self.vocab = Vocab(self.tokens, min_freq=1)
        self.pairs: list[tuple[list[int], int]]  = []
        
        for start in range(len(self.tokens) - self.window_size):
            end = start + self.window_size
            window = self.tokens[start:end]
            self.pairs.append((window[:-1], window[-1]))

    def __len__(self) -> int:
        return len(self.pairs)

    def __getitem__(self, idx: int) -> tuple[Tensor, int]:
        ctx, word = self.pairs[idx]
        ctx = torch.tensor([self.vocab.stoi(token) for token in ctx], dtype=torch.long)
        word = self.vocab.stoi(word)
        return ctx, word

Here we build two version of the dataset, one with a context size of one, only the previous word token, and one with a context size of eight.

Helper¶

The history serves the same purpose as for the previous chapters. It will hold and accumulate the metrics during training and allow to plot them in a summary graph. Here we are interested in the loss and the accruacy. Of course we could montior other textual metrics such as the perplexity, the blue score, the red score or others.

In [ ]:
class History:
    def __init__(self) -> None:
        self.loss = []
        self.acc = []

    def __len__(self) -> int:
        assert len(self.loss) == len(self.acc)
        return len(self.loss)

    def plot(self) -> None:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(2 * 4, 4), dpi=400)
        ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 1, 1)
        ax.plot(list(range(len(self))), self.loss, label="train", color="r")
        ax.set_title("Loss History")
        ax.set_xlabel("epoch")
        ax.set_ylabel("loss")
        ax.grid(linestyle="--", linewidth=0.5)
        ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)
        ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)
        ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
        ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
        ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 1, 2)
        ax.plot(list(range(len(self))), self.acc, label="train", color="b")
        ax.set_title("Accuracy History")
        ax.set_xlabel("epoch")
        ax.set_ylabel("accuracy in %")
        ax.set_ylim(0.0, 100.0)
        ax.grid(linestyle="--", linewidth=0.5)
        ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)
        ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)
        ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
        ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
        fig.canvas.draw()
        fig.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

Language Modeling¶

In this section, we study different type of Language Models, their advantages and drawbacks. The Language Model class handle the role of a common Interface for all the LM we build in the following sections.

In [ ]:
class LanguageModel(Module):
    def __init__(self, dataset: HarryPotterNextTokenDataset) -> None:
        super().__init__()
        self.dataset = dataset
        self.vocab = self.dataset.vocab

    def forward(self, x: Tensor, h: None | Tensor | tuple[Tensor, Tensor]) -> tuple[Tensor, None | Tensor | tuple[Tensor, Tensor]]:
        raise NotImplementedError

    @property
    def device(self) -> torch.DeviceObjType:
        return next(self.parameters()).device

    @property
    def vocab_size(self) -> int:
        return len(self.vocab)

We augment the LM class with a general fitting function as it will be the same for each and every LM version we build later. The fit function is responsible for training the LM model given an optimizer and common training hyperparemters. In this chapter we add a early stop mechanisme to stop trainning if no imporvement is made for a given amount of training epochs. This is not required bu will help us cut the training cost as the textual LM dataset are usually big.

In [ ]:
def fit(self: LanguageModel, optim: Optimizer, epochs: int, batch_size: int, idle_threshold: int = 4) -> History:
    loader = DataLoader(
        self.dataset,
        batch_size=batch_size,
        num_workers=4,
        pin_memory=True,
        shuffle=True,
        drop_last=True,
    )

    history = History()
    with tqdm(range(epochs), desc="Epoch") as pbar:
        best_state_dict, best_acc, best_step = {}, 0.0, 0
        for epoch in pbar:
            avg_loss, avg_acc = 0.0, 0.0
            for ctx, word in loader:
                ctx, word = ctx.to(self.device), word.to(self.device)

                y_, _ = self(ctx)
                loss = F.cross_entropy(y_, word)
                acc = (y_.argmax(dim=-1) == word).sum()

                optim.zero_grad(set_to_none=None)
                loss.backward()
                optim.step()

                avg_loss += loss.item() / len(loader)
                avg_acc  += acc.item()  / len(loader.dataset)
            
            history.loss.append(avg_loss)
            history.acc.append(avg_acc * 100)
            pbar.set_postfix(loss=f"{avg_loss:.2e}", acc=f"{avg_acc * 100:.2f}%")

            if avg_acc > best_acc:
                best_acc, best_step = avg_acc, 0
                best_state_dict = self.state_dict()
            else: best_step += 1
            
            if best_step >= idle_threshold:
                print(f"Training Stop Not Improving Since {best_step} Steps")
                break

    self.load_state_dict(best_state_dict)
    return history

LanguageModel.fit = fit

We also provide a general generation function generate that gives our LM the possibility to generate text given a context, a size, the size of the wanted generated text, and control parameters on the randomness of the produced output. One of these two control parameters is top_k. By assigning a value greater than $1$ to this argument will enable the use of the top $k$ token prediction to sample from using a weighted distribution based of the token probabilities. If $k$ is one, it is equivalent to using the token that is the most likely. Another parameter, the temperature, can also be used to flatten or sharpen the prediction probability distribution. By assigning a temperature closed to $0$ ($0$ would result in zero division) every token has the same probability, it anneals the distribution and makes it flat.

To make our generation method general, we assume that every language model outputs a tuple of Tensor (token probabilities), and the model's current internal sttate if any (set to None else).

In [ ]:
@torch.inference_mode()
def generate(self: LanguageModel, *ctx: tuple[str], length: int, temperature: float = 1.0, top_k: int = 1) -> list[str]:
    ctx, tokens = list(ctx), list(ctx)
    
    ctx, h = torch.tensor([self.vocab.stoi(t) for t in ctx], dtype=torch.long, device=self.device).unsqueeze(0), None
    for _ in range(length):
        logits, h = self(ctx, h)
        logits: Tensor = logits.squeeze(0) / temperature

        if top_k > 1:
            values, _ = torch.topk(logits, top_k)
            logits[logits < values[-1]] = -float("inf")

        probs: Tensor = torch.softmax(logits, dim=-1)
        idx = torch.multinomial(probs, num_samples=1) if top_k > 1 else probs.argmax()

        word = self.vocab.itos(idx.item())
        tokens.append(word)
        
        ctx[:, :-1] = ctx[:, 1:].clone()
        ctx[:, -1] = idx.clone()

    return tokens

LanguageModel.generate = generate

Bigram¶

One of the simplest LM one can think of is a transition probability map from one token to every others. It is equivalent to considering a context of size one and can be represented as a Transition Matrix. It is called a Bigram model. This Transition matrix can be sampled given a token to produce the next one. This idea can further be extended to bigger contexts.

Formulating the problem of LM as an optimization problem, it is possible to build such a matrix iteratively and make it fit to a specific distribution style, the writting style of a writter for example.

In [ ]:
class BigramLM(LanguageModel):
    def __init__(self, dataset: HarryPotterNextTokenDataset) -> None:
        super().__init__(dataset)
        self.logits = Parameter(torch.zeros((self.vocab_size, self.vocab_size)))

    def forward(self, x: Tensor, h: None = None) -> tuple[Tensor, None]:
        return self.logits[x.view(-1)], None

In the following cell, we augment the Bigram model with a plot method that enables visualization of the inner Transition Matrix.

In [ ]:
def plot(self: BigramLM, limit: int = 200) -> None:
    limit = 200
    heatmap = self.logits.cpu().detach().numpy().clip(0, 1)[:limit, :limit]
    words = list(self.vocab._stoi.keys())[:limit]

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8), dpi=600)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    im = ax.imshow(heatmap)
    ax.set_title("Bigram Heatmap")
    ax.tick_params(axis="both", which="both", length=0)
    ax.set_xticklabels(words, fontsize=2, rotation=90)
    ax.set_yticklabels(words, fontsize=2)
    ax.set_xticks(range(limit))
    ax.set_yticks(range(limit))
    ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
    fig.canvas.draw()
    plt.show()

BigramLM.plot = plot

Multi Layer Perceptron (MLP)¶

Another option for building a LM with the knowledge we acquired from the previous chapter is to use an Embedding to represent the words as compressed vectors in a trained latent space and use a MLP for classification. One drawback of such approach however is that the context size has to be fixed.

In [ ]:
class MultiLayerPerceptronLM(LanguageModel):
    def __init__(self, dataset: HarryPotterNextTokenDataset, emb_dim: int, h_dim: int) -> None:
        super().__init__(dataset)
        self.context_size = dataset.context_size
        self.embedding = Embedding(self.vocab_size, emb_dim)
        self.classifier = Sequential(
            Linear(emb_dim * self.context_size, h_dim), ReLU(),
            Linear(h_dim, self.vocab_size),
        )

    def forward(self, x: Tensor, h: None = None) -> tuple[Tensor, None]:
        x = self.embedding(x)
        x = x.reshape(x.size(0), -1)
        x = self.classifier(x)
        return x, None

Recurrent Neural Network (RNN)¶

MLPs are not designed to handle sequences of arbitrary size. Recurrent Neural Networks (RNN) have been expecially designed to work with sequences. It consists of an MLP that takes two input, a query and a context that is updated at each input. This acts as a memory, a vector that compresses previous information. During the backward pass, the error gradient will be backproagated through time.

While this approach allows us to handle arbitrary large sequences, it suffers from known limitations. It suffers from exploding and vanishing gradients. If the gradient at timestep $t$ is two small, it will not propagate back through time anymore. It it is two big, in will corrupt the early steps. Although we said it allows us to handle arbitraty sized input sequences, because of such problems and because of the simple memory mechanism, this architecture fails at capturing long term dependencies.

In [ ]:
class RecurrentNeuralNetworkLM(LanguageModel):
    def __init__(self, dataset: HarryPotterNextTokenDataset, emb_dim: int, h_dim: int, rnn: type[Module], n_layers: int) -> None:
        super().__init__(dataset)
        self.embedding = Embedding(self.vocab_size, emb_dim)
        self.rnn = rnn(emb_dim, h_dim, num_layers=n_layers, batch_first=True)
        self.classifier = Linear(h_dim, self.vocab_size)

    def forward(self, x: Tensor, h: Tensor | tuple[Tensor, Tensor] = None) -> tuple[Tensor, Tensor | tuple[Tensor, Tensor]]:
        x = self.embedding(x)
        x, h = self.rnn(x, h)
        x = self.classifier(x[:, -1, :])
        return x, h

Long Short Term Memory (LSTM)¶

To counter the issues introduced by the Vanilla RNN, complex memory mechanisms have been introduced in the literature. One of them, certainly the most popular, is the Long Short Term Memory (LSTM). It uses several gating procedures to modify two states, one for short term memory and another for long term memory. The LSTM cell comprises $3$ gates, the forget gate to erase unecessary information from the long term memory given the current input and the previous short term state, an input gate to select which information to keep in memory, and lastly an output gate using the current states to output the next token.

Such complex machinery allows to go beyond the limitations of the vanilla RNN and handle up two a thousand length sequences depending on the task complexity.

Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU)¶

While the LSTM is a grate successor of the RNN cell, it does not come at no cost. It is heavier to compute as each gate involves a non linear layer with its weights. Simpler mechansims have been proposed to eleviate this problem. One of them is the Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU). The GRU sacrifices accuracy for speed.

Attention Mechanism¶

Not every element of a sequence is important when taking a decision. When we, as humans, take a look at a sentence, we only focus on subsections of greater importance and use them as vectors for our context that allows us to answer questions on the nature of the data, and take informed decisions. This process is called Attention. Similar mechanisms have been created for sequence learning, such as the Additive Attention, the Multplicative Attention, more recently the Self Attention, and many others (e.g. Cross Attention).

Here we implement a simple Self Attention mechanism. As will see in the next chapters it is the building block for an entire state of the art architecture family, the Transformers.

In [ ]:
class Attention(Module):
    def __init__(self, h_dim: int) -> None:
        super().__init__()
        self.q = Linear(h_dim, h_dim)
        self.k = Linear(h_dim, h_dim)
        self.v = Linear(h_dim, h_dim)

    def forward(self, q: Tensor, k: Tensor, v: Tensor) -> Tensor:
        scale = 1. / np.sqrt(q.size(-1))
        q = q.transpose(0, 1)
        q, k, v = self.q(q), self.k(k), self.v(v)
        k = k.permute(0, 2, 1)
        e = torch.softmax(scale * torch.bmm(q, k), dim=2)
        return torch.bmm(e, v).squeeze(1)


class AttentionRecurrentNeuralNetworkLM(LanguageModel):
    def __init__(self, dataset: HarryPotterNextTokenDataset, emb_dim: int, h_dim: int, rnn: type[Module]) -> None:
        super().__init__(dataset)
        self.embedding = Embedding(self.vocab_size, emb_dim)
        self.rnn = rnn(emb_dim, h_dim, batch_first=True)
        self.attention = Attention(h_dim)
        self.classifier = Linear(h_dim, self.vocab_size)

    def forward(self, x: Tensor, h: Tensor | tuple[Tensor, Tensor] = None) -> tuple[Tensor, Tensor | tuple[Tensor, Tensor]]:
        x = self.embedding(x)
        x, h = self.rnn(x, h)
        x = self.attention(h[1] if isinstance(h, tuple) else h, x, x)
        x = self.classifier(x)
        return x, h
